   "evidence": "grep of mathlib shows EquivOf* exclusively names hypotheses (EquivOfSurjective/Injective/Comm/Le/Iso/IsUniformInducing); decl is in `namespace AddCircle` so full name is `AddCircle.fundamentalGroupMulEquivOfAddCircle`; sibling `Deck.addCircleMulEquivInt` already uses the `Int` suffix for the same `Multiplicative \u2124` target.",
   "file": "TauCeti/AlgebraicTopology/UniversalCover/CircleFundamentalGroup.lean",
   "fix": "Rename to `fundamentalGroupMulEquivInt`, matching the adjacent `Deck.addCircleMulEquivInt` (also a `Multiplicative \u2124` target); rename the three dependent lemmas accordingly.",
   "issue": "`AddCircle.fundamentalGroupMulEquivOfAddCircle` misuses the `\u2026EquivOf<X>` convention, which in Mathlib names a *hypothesis/property* (EquivOfSurjective, EquivOfInjective, EquivOfIso, EquivOfComm), never the object. Here `AddCircle` is the object \u2014 and it is already the enclosing namespace, so `OfAddCircle` is redundant and the `Of` falsely suggests a hypothesis. It also fails to distinguish this from `fundamentalGroupMulEquiv`, since both produce `Multiplicative \u2124`; the real difference is generality.",
